Day 7 code
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.user-card {
border: 1px solid #ddd;
border-radius: 8px;
padding: 12px;
margin: 8px 0;
}
.user-card h3 {
margin: 0 0 6px;
}
#status {
color: gray;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<button id="loadBtn">Load User</button>
<p id="status"></p>
<div id="userList"></div> <script>
const btn = document.getElementById("loadBtn");
const status = document.getElementById("status");
const userList = document.getElementById("userList");
btn.addEventListener("click", async () => {
status.textContent = "Loading...";
btn.disabled = true;
try {
const resp = await fetch(
"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users",
);
if (!resp.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${resp.status}`);
const users = await resp.json();
const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
for (const user of users) {
const card = document.createElement("div");
card.className = "user-card";
const name = document.createElement("h3");
name.textContent = user.name;
const email = document.createElement("p");
email.textContent = `📧 ${user.email}`;
card.append(name, email);
fragment.appendChild(card);
}
userList.innerHTML = "";
userList.appendChild(fragment);
status.textContent = ` ${users.length} users are loaded`;
} catch (err) {
status.textContent = "Failture:" + err.message;
} finally {
btn.disabled = false;
}
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
This code fetches user information from a publicly accessible API and displays it on the webpage. The data-fetching operation is triggered when the user clicks the “Load User” button.
In this example, we will skip the CSS in the <style> element and the HTML structure, as they are quite similar to those in the previous examples. Instead, we will focus on DOM manipulation with JavaScript.
1/ Add a listener
btn.addEventListener("click", callback)This line adds an event listener to the button to detect click events. When the user clicks the button, the callback function runs, starting the entire process.
2/ Fetch and Load Json from API
const resp = await fetch(
"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users",
);
if (!resp.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${resp.status}`);
const users = await resp.json();Inside the callback function, fetch() sends a request to the specified API. If the request is unsuccessful, an error containing the HTTP status code is thrown. Otherwise, the JSON response is parsed into a JavaScript value and stored in the users variable.
3/ Create temporary staging area
const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
for (const user of users) {
const card = document.createElement("div");
card.className = "user-card"; const name = document.createElement("h3");
name.textContent = user.name;
const email = document.createElement("p");
email.textContent = `📧 ${user.email}`;
card.append(name, email);
fragment.appendChild(card);
}
Next, a DocumentFragment is created as a temporary staging area. The loop iterates over every user object in the users array. For each user, it creates a card containing the user’s name and email address, then appends the completed card to the fragment.
4/ Move the created content
userList.innerHTML = "";
userList.appendChild(fragment);First, the existing content in userList is cleared. Then, all the newly created user cards are moved from the document fragment into userList and displayed on the webpage.
